{{short description|15th-century Ottoman historian}} {{cleanup|date=October 2013|reason=Remove the link 'Some information in Turkish' as it provides little useful information for en WP readers. Please expedite }} {{Ottoman Turkish name|Oruç|Bey}} {{Infobox Muslim scholar |era = [[Ottoman Empire]] |image = |caption = |name = Oruç Bey |title= |birth_date = |death_date = |Maddhab = |school_tradition= |ethnicity = |region = |main_interests = Ottoman history |notable_ideas= |works = "Oruç Bey Tarihi" ("The History of Oruç Bey") | influences = | influenced = }}
'''Oruç Bey''' was a 15th-century [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] historian.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rogers|first1=Clifford J.|last2=DeVries|first2=Kelly|last3=France|first3=John|year=2012|title=The Ottoman-Hungarian Campaigns of 1442|journal=Journal of Medieval Military History|volume=10|page=153|publisher=Boydell Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_7GybW-t-7YC&pg=PA153&dq=oruc+bey+tarihi&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=UvbRUazzNoLLtQaa0ICoBg&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=oruc%20bey%20tarihi&f=false}}</ref>
==Life and career== Almost nothing is known from his personal life. Based on the information in the intro of his chronicle, it is believed that he was a [[clerk]] born in [[Edirne]] and that his father was a [[silk]] manufacturer.
==Works== Oruç Bey's work is called ''Oruç Bey Tarihi'' ("The History of Oruç Bey"), sometimes named similarly to other Ottoman chronicles "Tevarih-i Al-i Osman" (History of the house of Osman). It is written in [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] and describes the Ottoman history till [[Hijri year|Hegira]] 907 ([[anno Domini|anno]]1501/1502). His chronicle is considered as an important source for the history of the early Ottoman Empire.
==Bibliography== * Franz Babinger, Berlin, "Die frühosmaischen Jahrbücher des Urudsch"
